snippet.textDisplay:
Novak received a medical clearance from Tennis Australia who are a commercial organization who have no right to give an exemption, medical or otherwise. The Australian state of Victoria gave him a medical exemption to enter the state of Victoria BUT that state is part of the country of Australia and the country of Australia has a policy of double-vaccinated entry only. Novak bluffed his way passed the quarantine authorities at the country's border and when he was called to account and his entry visa was cancelled he successfully  appealed to the Federal Circuit Court. The federal authorities overruled the decision of the court and cancelled his visa again on grounds of health and public order, which he unsuccessfully appealed to the full bench of the Federal Court, and he was subsequently deported as an illegal entrant to the country as he no longer had a valid visa. 

The law as applied to him is the same law and same method of application as applies to everyone else in the country. If you object to his deportation then you are advocating that he be above the law. If he had managed to pull that off, he would have been booed off the court and spat on if he managed to go out in public. There would have been confrontation between his supporters and detractors  on a significant scale. The marvelous levels of vaccination (currently over 90%) in the country would have been held up to ridicule and the nation's health undermined, especially amongst Aboriginal and refugee populations who have distinctly lower vaccination rates and higher co-morbidity health conditions.

The same approach has been taken to exclude Holocaust denial advocates, as well as extreme Fascists and Socialists, etc. etc. 

As such I'm glad Novak's gone, so I can get down to watching some serious tennis, with an ice-cold drink in one hand, while sitting in the shade from the summer sun glinting of the turquoise surf being enjoyed by almost all.
